Frontline health care worker sub-groups for prioritisation-->    frontline staff in facilities or services such as hospital emergency departments,COVID-19 and respiratory wards, Intensive Care Units and High-dependency Units  laboratory staff handling potentially infectious material  ambulance and paramedics service  GP respiratory clinics, and    COVID-19 testing facilities.    *All other healthcare workers are included in Phase 1b, including medical and tertiary students with placements in these healthcare settings.       Aged care and disability care staff-->    people who provide weekly informal care to a person with a disability in a residential care setting  people classified as an essential care person in a residential aged care setting     Aged care and disability care residents-->         Phase 1b   Elderly adults aged 80 years and over  Elderly adults aged 70-79 years  Other health care workers  Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people > 55  Adults with an underlying medical condition, including those with a disability       *People will need to provide proof of these conditions to demonstrate their eligibility for vaccination via My health record, a health professional referral if required or a declaration form. column159: COVID-19 vaccines will be voluntary and free  The COVID-19 vaccine is free for everyone in Australia. Vaccination providers cannot charge you for the COVID-19 vaccine or your appointments to receive the vaccine.    If your vaccination provider charges for any costs associated with the administration of the COVID-19 vaccination (including booking fees), you should:    contact us by emailing provider.benefits.integrity@health.gov.au,  or call the Provider Benefits Integrity Hotline on 1800 314 808 (9am to 5pm AEST weekdays).    https://web.archive.org/web/20210423124712/https://www.health.gov.au/initiatives-and-programs/covid-19-vaccines/getting-vaccinated-for-covid-19

Unlike the almost 250,000 Pfizer vaccinations that have been administered as part of the invitation-only phase 1a, the Australians eligible under phase 1b are able to book vaccine appointments as soon as the phase begins. column55: 1 July- Vaccination strategy *recommendations* in Belgium published. Recorded here as a note as they are only recommended, not yet official policy.    The SHC (Superior Health Council) recommends to prioritize the following groups for vaccination against Covid-19  based on the available data and statistical evidence:    - All workers in the health care sector to secure their health and a working health care  sector during a potential next COVID-19 wave or pandemic;  - All people above 65 years of age;  - Patients between 45 and 65 years with the following comorbidities which are at risk for  developing severe COVID-19: obesity, diabetes, hypertension, chronic  cardiovascular, lung, kidney and liver diseases and haematological  malignancies up to 5 years from diagnosis and all recent solid cancers (or recent  cancer treatments).    Further prioritisation inside the above groups may be considered if a limited amount of vaccine is available.  This recommendation can be changed according to new data and information on immunogenicity of the type of vaccine(s) that will be available. For instance, we will further follow data regarding pregnant woman, other immunocompromised patients as well as the  impact of socio-economical and ethnic background.     https://web.archive.org/web/20210505131244/https://www.health.belgium.be/sites/default/files/uploads/fields/fpshealth_theme_file/201030_shc-9597_9611_vaccination_strategy_covid_19_vweb_0.pdf

First archive of priority list on government website published 22 December 2020    GROUP I    First, the most vulnerable and exposed people will be vaccinated.    Residents and employees of residential care centres and collective care institutions: since the outbreak of the pandemic, COVID-19 has hit elderly people hard, especially those living in residential care centres. They will be vaccinated first, followed by the staff working there (including volunteers), followed by collective care institutions.  Primary care and hospital staff: the next target group are the healthcare professionals in hospitals and those in the front line who are affected by the virus. These people have daily and close contact with patients suffering from Covid-19. To protect them, they are vaccinated as a matter of priority.  The other staff in hospitals and health services: then, the other staff in hospitals and health services will be vaccinated, including organisations responsible for prevention activities, such as vaccination and cancer screening centres, ONE and Kind en Gezin.  In this first phase, this will require a special organisation and infrastructure (extremely low storage temperatures, multiple doses, etc.).    GROUP 2 - vulnerable population not receiving acute medical care but at high risk    In a second phase, it is expected that the vaccine will become more widely available. It will then be possible to vaccinate larger groups of people. In this second phase, priority will be given to people who are not in hospital, who are most at risk in the population. These are the following groups of people:    People over 65: people over 65 are the first priority at this stage. If sufficient vaccine is available, all these people can be vaccinated at the same time. Otherwise we start with the oldest people.  People between 45-65 years of age with an increased risk: Next up are people between 45-65 years of age increased risk factors or high risks, such as:  Diabetes,  Hypertension,  Chronic cardiovascular, pulmonary, kidney and liver disorders, haematological malignancies up to 5 years after diagnosis,  All recent cancers (or recent cancer treatments)  Body Mass Index = 30  The list of persons involved will be updated and extended as scientific developments progress.    Essential professions In this phase, people with essential social and/or economic profession are vaccinated. In this second phase, we can expect fewer logistical bottlenecks and organising the vaccination will be easier for these target groups.  GROUP 3 - general population    Thirdly, vaccine doses will be available in sufficient quantities to vaccinate the general population.    At this stage it can be expected that the doses can be stored and administered like other vaccines such as the flu shot. Storage and administration restrictions should allow for larger scale vaccination.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201222182249/https://www.info-coronavirus.be/en/vaccination/#targetgroup

Residents of nursing homes are among the priority groups to receive the first dose of the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine on Jan. 5, and the second one will be given in three weeks. column55: Media source reports that police are added as a priority group following an update to Vaccination strategy as a result of Astra Zeneca. This does not appear on the official priority list however and I cannot find an official source to confirm. I have added them to the list with the more general 'frontline workers' category    Media source: https://web.archive.org/web/20210506101510/https://www.brusselstimes.com/news/belgium-all-news/153255/belgium-updates-vaccination-strategy-due-to-astrazeneca-vaccine-pfizer-biontech-moderna-pierre-van-damme-taskforce/    Second media source mentioning addition of police:  https://web.archive.org/web/20210506102056/https://www.brusselstimes.com/news/belgium-all-news/153314/police-in-critical-functions-will-be-vaccinated-from-mid-february-verlinden-field-coronavirus-astrazeneca/    Priority list order remains the same but has been split into '1a' and '1b'    GROUP 1a    In the first instance, the most vulnerable and exposed people will receive the vaccine.    - Residents and employees in residential care centres and collective care institutions: since the outbreak of the pandemic, COVID-19 has hit the elderly particularly hard, principally those in residential care centres. They will be vaccinated first, then the corresponding staff (including volunteers), followed by collective care institutions.  - Medical personnel from first-line care and hospitals: they are in close contact with COVID-19 patients every day. To protect them, they will be prioritised for vaccination.  - The other staff in hospitals and healthcare centres will be vaccinated, including organisations which work in prevention activities, such as vaccination centres and cancer screening centres, Child and Family and ONE.    This first phase will require a special organisation and infrastructure (extremely low storage temperatures, multiple doses, and so on).    GROUP 1b : vulnerable people without acute medical issues, but at high risk    In this phase, it is expected that vaccines will become available on a large scale. It will then be possible to vaccinate larger groups of people. Priority will be given to people outside hospitals, who are at the highest risk. It concerns the following groups:    - People over the age of 65 : people older than 65 will be a priority in this phase. If there is sufficient vaccine available, these people will be vaccinated simultaneously. Otherwise, we will start with the oldest people and then go down through the age groups.  - People between 45 and 65 with an increased risk: People aged between 45 and 65 with risk factors such as:  - Diabetes,  - Hypertension,  - Chronic cardiovascular, lung, kidney and liver disease, haematological cancers up to 5 years after diagnosis,  - All recent cancers (or recent treatments against cancer)  - Obesity (Body Mass Index = 30).  - The detailed lists will be published after scientific advice.    Essential roles: This phase will include people who fulfil essential social and/or economic roles. In the second phase, we can expect logistical issues to have been ironed out so that the provision of the vaccine to these target groups will run more smoothly.    GROUP 2 - broader population    Government priority list source: https://web.archive.org/web/20210210103909/https://www.info-coronavirus.be/en/vaccination/

column107: From mid-February , injection of the AZ vaccine will begin for as many people as possible in the following groups, in this order:    - the professional health care 18 to 55 years .    - the residents and staff (18-55) other collective care institutions, such as the centers of rehabilitation, psychiatric institutions or the personal protection residential institutions for Children and Youth. column107: Phase 1B: begins in March.    The Brussels-Capital Region has started the vaccination of its inhabitants with co-morbidities against the coronavirus, the Regions Common Community Commission (COCOM) said on Friday. The region is in vaccination phase 1b, which covers people who are over the age of 65, as well as people between 18 and 64 years old, who have been prioritised as they run a greater risk of ending up in hospital when infected with the virus.    All regions in the country receive the same number of doses of coronavirus vaccines in proportion to the number of inhabitants, however, Brussels is ahead of Flanders in starting to vaccinate this high-risk patients group.    https://archive.vn/HWxcn

On 30 December, vaccinations began in remote indigenous communities in British Columbia (BC). Members of three groups -- long-term care residents, frontline workers, remote indigenous community residents -- have now been vaccinated somewhere in Canada. Vaccinations are expected to start soon in indigenous communities in other provinces. https://web.archive.org/web/20210103010814/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-vaccine-rollout-picks-up-speed-in-first-nations-across-canada/  https://web.archive.org/web/20210104162416/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/covid-19-vaccine/bcs-plan-for-vaccine-distribution    On 20 January 2021, Indigenous Services Canada announced: The rollout of the vaccines to many First Nations, Inuit, and Mtis communities has started. Vaccine administration continues within communities, thanks to the commitment of Indigenous leadership and health experts, and federal, provincial, Indigenous collaboration, including on logistics and data sharing. To date vaccination has begun in 169 communities for First Nations or Inuit in all provinces and territories except Nova Scotia and PEI. Covid vaccinations (Pfizer and Moderna) in Canada are being administered to 3 groups -- A. key workers (front-line health sector), B. clinically vulnerable groups (remote indigenous communities and federal prisoners at risk due to age or other health problems), C. elderly groups (residents of long-term care facilities and retirement homes). See Government of Canada and Globe and Mail newspaper websites, archived:  https://web.archive.org/web/20210126020941/https://www.canada.ca/en/indigenous-services-canada/news/2021/01/government-of-canada-covid-19-update-for-indigenous-peoples-and-communities1.html  https://web.archive.org/web/20210126024649/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/politics/article-older-at-risk-federal-inmates-to-receive-shot-sparking-criticism-from/

column55: The following target groups are to be prioritised for vaccination:    1 People at especially high risk (excluding pregnant women)  2 Healthcare professionals with patient contact/carers for persons at especially high risk  3 Close contacts (household members) of people at especially high risk  4 People in communal facilities with an increased risk of infection and outbreaks (with residents of mixed ages).  As the next stage, vaccination will be possible for all other adults not in groups 1 - 4 above.    There is no mandatory vaccination requirement. The COVID-19 vaccination will be free of charge for the population.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201220001414/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/impfen.html#-1016131036    *Coding notes, coded 'people in communal facilities' as 'crowded accommodation' AND 'disabled people' as a best fit.

column159: Coverage of vaccination costs  The costs of a COVID-19 vaccination are covered by mandatory health insurance. The costs that are not covered by health insurance are borne by the federal government and the cantons.    The vaccination is thus free of charge for people with mandatory health insurance in Switzerland. You do not have to pay any deductible or copayment.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210422114424/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/impfen.html

column55: Priority list updated on 30 December 2020:    Who is to be vaccinated?  The plan is to prioritise vaccination of target groups of people age 16 as follows:    Target group 1: People at especially high risk (vulnerable people; excluding pregnant women)  Target group 2: Healthcare professionals with patient contact/carers for people at especially high risk  Target group 3: Close contacts (household members) of people at especially high risk  Target group 4: People in communal facilities with an increased risk of infection and outbreaks (for example homes for the handicapped).  Given that as vaccination starts there are not sufficient doses of vaccine available, further prioritisation is necessary within target group 1.    The following people are to be given access to vaccinations first:    People age 75 and over  People with chronic diseases of the highest risk, regardless of their age  After that come:    People aged between 65 and 74  People under 65 and people with chronic diseases who have not yet been vaccinated    Following people in target group 1, the vaccination will be offered to people in target groups 2, 3 and 4 in that order. In due course adults who are not in target groups 1 to 4 will also be able to have the vaccination.    It is not yet planned to vaccinate children. Study data for the relevant age groups is not yet available.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201231115345/https://www.bag.admin.ch/bag/en/home/krankheiten/ausbrueche-epidemien-pandemien/aktuelle-ausbrueche-epidemien/novel-cov/impfen.html

On 17 December 2020 STIKO has published a more precise hierarchy of the framework above, based on scientific data. This will enable to communicate transparently the evidence-based rationale of the priority levels given to different groups. This hierarchy organised into six groups is expected to be updated throughout the pandemic, as the situation develops and more evidence and resources (e.g. new vaccines) become available:    Group 1 includes people living in care and nursing homes, people aged 80 years and older, staff working in health care settings with particularly high risk of exposure (e.g. A&E, staff caring for COVID-19 patients), staff in health care setting in close contact with groups at particularly high risk (e.g. Haemato-oncology, transplant medicine), care workers in domiciliary and residential long-term care for older people and others working in care and nursing homes in contact with residents. It is estimated that this group amounts to 8.6 million people.[3]    Group 2 includes people aged 75 to 79 years, staff in medical care settings with high risk of exposure, people with dementia and mental disabilities living in residential care settings, people working domiciliary and residential care with people with dementia or people with mental disabilities as well as people living with Down-Syndrome. This group includes an estimated 7 million people.[4]    Group 3 covers approximately 5.7 million people[5]  and includes those aged 70 to 74 years, people who have had an organ transplant; people with pre-existing conditions and who are at high risk, people living in sheltered accommodation/refuges and staff; close contacts of pregnant women; close contacts/family carers of people at high risk; staff at moderate risk of exposure in health care settings and in positions relevant to maintaining hospital infrastructure; parts of the public health authorities.    Group 4 (approximately 4.9 million people[6]) consists of those aged 65 to 69 years; people with pre-existing conditions who are at moderate risk and their closest contacts, staff working in health care settings with low risk of exposure, teachers, educators, people in precarious work or living situations.    People aged 60 to 64 years, staff in key local and federal government positions, people working in retail; people required to maintain public security with heightened risk of exposure and people working in critical infrastructure fall into Group 5 (about 8.4 million people[7]).    The final group consists of the remaining population aged younger than 60 years (approximately 45 million people[8]).    https://archive.vn/VR2fb

column107: A 101-year-old woman in a nursing home in Saxony-Anhalt has become one of Germany's first people to get vaccinated against coronavirus.  BioNTech-Pfizer vaccinations kicked off in the state of Saxony-Anhalt on Saturday, a day before Germany officially launches its coronavirus vaccination campaign.  In Halberstadt, 101-year-old Edith Kwoizalla was the first resident of the town's Krueger center for senior citizens to receive the jab. Forty residents and 10 staff members at the center were reportedly vaccinated.    https://archive.vn/DwB70  https://archive.vn/vbXjx  https://archive.vn/0tNEl

column55: On 17 December 2020 STIKO has published a more precise hierarchy of the framework above, based on scientific data. This will enable to communicate transparently the evidence-based rationale of the priority levels given to different groups. This hierarchy organised into six groups is expected to be updated throughout the pandemic, as the situation develops and more evidence and resources (e.g. new vaccines) become available: Group 1 includes people living in care and nursing homes, people aged 80 years and older, staff working in health care settings with particularly high risk of exposure (e.g. A&E, staff caring for COVID-19 patients), staff in health care setting in close contact with groups at particularly high risk (e.g. Haemato-oncology, transplant medicine), care workers in domiciliary and residential long-term care for older people and others working in care and nursing homes in contact with residents. It is estimated that this group amounts to 8.6 million people.[3] Group 2 includes people aged 75 to 79 years, staff in medical care settings with high risk of exposure, people with dementia and mental disabilities living in residential care settings, people working domiciliary and residential care with people with dementia or people with mental disabilities as well as people living with Down-Syndrome. This group includes an estimated 7 million people.[4] Group 3 covers approximately 5.7 million people[5] and includes those aged 70 to 74 years, people who have had an organ transplant; people with pre-existing conditions and who are at high risk, people living in sheltered accommodation/refuges and staff; close contacts of pregnant women; close contacts/family carers of people at high risk; staff at moderate risk of exposure in health care settings and in positions relevant to maintaining hospital infrastructure; parts of the public health authorities. Group 4 (approximately 4.9 million people[6]) consists of those aged 65 to 69 years; people with pre-existing conditions who are at moderate risk and their closest contacts, staff working in health care settings with low risk of exposure, teachers, educators, people in precarious work or living situations. People aged 60 to 64 years, staff in key local and federal government positions, people working in retail; people required to maintain public security with heightened risk of exposure and people working in critical infrastructure fall into Group 5 (about 8.4 million people[7]). The final group consists of the remaining population aged younger than 60 years (approximately 45 million people[8]). https://archive.vn/VR2fb

column55: 26 Nov 2020    Yesterday evening (November 26 2020) the government revealed its plans for when and how people in Denmark will be vaccinated for the coronavirus.    The National Board of Health has established a priority order for offers of vaccination against COVID-19.     We have divided the population into 10 prioritised target groups to be vaccinated in the following order:    1. Residents in nursing homes, assisted living, etc.     2. People aged = 65 who receive both personal care and practical assistance.     3. People aged = 85 years.     4. Personnel in healthcare, elderly care and selected parts of the social sector who are at particular risk of infection or who has been identified as performing a critical function in society.     5. Selected persons with conditions and diseases that result in a significantly increased risk of severe illness from COVID-19.     6. Selected relatives of individuals at significantly increased risk of a severe illness from COVID-19 or relatives who are indispensable as caregivers.     7. People aged 80-84.     8. People aged 75-79.    9. People aged 65-74.    10 A. People aged 60-64 (born between 1957 and 1961).    10 B. People aged 55-59 (born between 1962 and 1966).    10 C. People aged 50-54 (born between 1967 and 1971).    10 D1. People aged 16-19 and 45-49 years (born 1972-1976 and 2002-2005).    10 D2. People aged 20-24 and 40-44 years (born 1977-1981 and 1997-2001).    10 D3. People aged 25-29 and 35-39 years (born 1982-1986 and 1992-1996).    10 D4. People aged 30-34 (born 1987-1991).      Media source on announcement of groups: https://web.archive.org/web/20210506161940/https://cphpost.dk/?p=120805    Priority groups: https://web.archive.org/web/20210506161003/https://www.sst.dk/en/english/corona-eng/vaccination-against-covid-19/who-should-be-vaccinated    Calendar: https://web.archive.org/web/20210108152822/https://www.sst.dk/da/Udgivelser/2021/Vaccinationskalender    Calendar: https://web.archive.org/web/20210108155223/https://www.sst.dk/-/media/Udgivelser/2021/Corona/Vaccination/Kalender/Vaccinationskalender-8-jan.ashx?la=da&hash=4730B8DBB5CF05DB61AE6ABEBA171CC78692BD72

column55: The first stage of vaccination prioritisation is for residents and staff in homes for seniors and the disabled, healthcare workers and adults with dependencies who are not in institutions. No specific rank was given to these, so they are all ranked equal importance. https://web.archive.org/web/20210506124121/https://english.elpais.com/society/2020-12-29/more-than-350000-doses-of-the-covid-19-vaccine-arrive-in-spain-as-mass-immunization-campaign-begins.html At the present time, vaccination of the groups initially prioritized in the first stage can be considered almost complete: Residents and health and social health personnel who work in nursing homes and care for large dependents Frontline personnel in the health and social health field Other health and social health personnel (not included in the previous group) who perform activities that require close contact with people who may be infected with SARS-CoV-2. Priority has been given to personnel in the hospital and primary care environment not considered frontline. Dental, dental hygiene and other health personnel who care for people without a mask for more than 15 minutes have also been vaccinated Persons considered as large dependents (grade III of dependency, that is, with the need for intense support measures) not institutionalized. THEN: People over 80 years of age (born in 1941 and in previous years). They will be vaccinated with mRNA vaccines developed by Pfizer/BioNTech and Moderna People between 70 and 79 years old. They will be vaccinated with mRNA vaccines (Pfizer/BioNTech and Moderna) or with Janssen vaccine People with very high-risk conditions from 16-18 years old. They will be vaccinated in parallel with the previous group: hematopoietic progenitor transplantation, solid organ transplantation and waiting list for solid organ transplantation, renal replacement treatment (hemodialysis and peritoneal dialysis), oncohematological disease, solid organ cancer being treated with cytotoxic, metastatic chemotherapy or with radiation therapy for chest-localized tumors at risk of pneumonitis, primary immunodeficiencies, HIV infection with less than 200 cell/ml despite effective ART and undetectable viral load and Down syndrome over 40 years of age. These people (dependents and professional caregivers) will be vaccinated with mRNA, Janssen or Vaxzevria, the AstraZeneca vaccine, depending on the age of the person and availability People between 60 and 65 years old. They will be vaccinated starting with people aged 60 in ascending order of age with the AstraZeneca vaccine People between 66 and 69 years old. They will be vaccinated with the AstraZeneca vaccine although the vaccination of this group can be completed with the vaccine that is available Once vaccinated, the population over 60 years of age will be vaccinated or completed vaccination of: Public health personnel, health inspection services, forensic and forensic medicine, private medical consultations, home help services, juvenile centers and day centers or equivalent, health and social health students, physiotherapists, occupational therapists, pharmacy office staff, dental technicians, speech therapists and clinical psychology personnel, prison workers Other health and social health personnel not vaccinated previously Collectives with an essential function for society The next group to be vaccinated will be: People between 50 and 59 years old

column55: In its negotiations on 2 December, the Government approved the Finnish COVID-19 vaccine strategy prepared by the Ministry of Social Affairs and Health. This will be approved in the coming weeks.    Coronary vaccination is provided based on a medical risk assessment. Initially, the vaccine is offered to the following groups:    - social and health care staff caring for coronary patients and staff in nursing homes  - the elderly  - persons with diseases predisposing to severe coronavirus disease    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207005233/https://vnk.fi/-/0212-luonnos

The Government decided on Finlands vaccination order by adopting a Decree on 22 December 2020. The Finnish Institute for Health and Welfare recommends that COVID-19 vaccinations are offered to different groups in the following order:   1. Health care personnel caring for coronavirus patients as well as personnel and residents in round-the-clock care facilities   1.1 Personnel in intensive care units   1.2 Personnel in inpatient wards and emergency wards treating diagnosed or suspected COVID-19 patients and emergency care personnel   1.3 Personnel at infectious diseases clinics treating diagnosed or suspected COVID-19 patients, COVID-19 testing personnel, and laboratory personnel involved in COVID-19 diagnostics   1.4 Personnel and residents in social services for residential care and enhanced institutional, round-the-clock care units (groups 3 and 4 may be vaccinated simultaneously)   1.5 A limited number of critical personnel in social welfare and health care, for example, personnel in organ transplant units     2.1 The elderly, and persons with underlying conditions that predispose to severe COVID-19 2.1.1. 80-year-olds and older, including carers and elderly living in the same household   2.1.2. 7579-year-olds, including carers and elderly living in the same household   2.1.3. 7074-year-olds, including carers and elderly living in the same household   2.1.4. 16-69-year-olds with a highly predisposing condition for severe COVID-19. Highly predisposing conditions for severe COVID-19 disease include, for example, severe chronic kidney disease, severe immunosuppressive condition (organ transplant, acute cancer treatment) and severe chronic pulmonary disease.   2.1.5. 18-69-year-olds with a predisposing condition for severe COVID-19. Predisposing conditions for severe COVID-19 include, for example, coronary artery disease and cirrhosis of the liver.   2.2 Social welfare and health care personnel   3. Others The vaccination order now contains underlying diseases that have been shown by research to contribute most to severe COVID-19 disease.   Details of the vaccination order of persons under 70 who have other diseases, or who are completely healthy, will be given later. Once the number of vaccinations arriving in Finland is significantly higher, the vaccinations will be extended to the entire adult population. Why are special groups, such as people with disabilities, not mentioned in the risk groups in the vaccination order? The vaccination order in Finland has been prepared on the basis of a medical risk assessment at the population level, i.e. according to the level of risk a certain group has for a serious coronavirus disease. The aim is to offer vaccines as fairly as possible to those who need them most. People whose underlying disease or condition exposes them to serious coronavirus disease are included in the coronavirus risk groups. Underlying diseases and conditions are divided into two groups depending on the degree of exposure caused by the disease or condition. Some of those belonging to special groups will be vaccinated on the basis of their underlying disease. https://web.archive.org/web/20210507133613/https://thl.fi/en/web/infectious-diseases-and-vaccinations/what-s-new/coronavirus-covid-19-latest-updates/transmission-and-protection-coronavirus/vaccines-and-coronavirus/vaccination-order-and-at-risk-groups-for-covid-19

column107: Finland will begin inoculating residents on Sunday, 27 December after receiving its first allotment of Pfizer and BioNTechs Covid-19 vaccine on Saturday. Front-line ICU healthcare workers will be the first to get the jab, followed by healthcare personnel working with Covid patients. https://web.archive.org/web/20210507140949/https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/finland_receives_first_batch_of_covid_vaccines/11715053 http://web.archive.org/web/20210109024138/https://yle.fi/uutiset/osasto/news/covid_vaccine_rolls_out_in_tampere_turku_kuopio_and_oulu/11715952 This article from 21 Jan states that most of the following have been vaccinated, so I have coded them as eligible from the first date of vaccination as unable to find progressive announcements of expanding eligibility between December and January : 'intensive care personnel, social and health care employees caring for coronavirus patients, and the residents and personnel of care homes for the elderly' https://web.archive.org/web/20210507144904/https://thl.fi/en/web/thlfi-en/-/national-vaccine-specialists-coronavirus-vaccinations-must-move-ahead-rapidly-and-flexibly-to-protect-the-elderly?redirect=%2Fen%2Fweb%2Finfectious-diseases-and-vaccinations%2Fwhat-s-new%2Fcoronavirus-covid-19-latest-updates%2Fsituation-update-on-coronavirus This article from 29 January 2021 also states that vaccinations for all people in the 1'st group began being vaccinated in December 2020, so have coded them as eligible from the start too: "1. Healthcare staff caring for coronary patients and 24-hour care staff and residents 1. 1. Staff in power departments Almost the entire group has been vaccinated. 1.2. Staff in inpatient and emergency departments and emergency departments treating identified or suspected covid-19 patients Almost the entire group has been vaccinated. 1.3. Staff at infection centers, corona sampling staff and laboratory staff performing coronavirus diagnosis in patients diagnosed or suspected with covid-19 Almost the entire group has been vaccinated. 1.4. Residents and staff of the elderly social care housing services and the intensive care unit, ie 24-hour care The group is currently being vaccinated. column55: List remains the same as previous:    The Government decided on Finlands vaccination order by adopting a Decree on 22 December 2020.    The Finnish Institute for Health and Welfare recommends that COVID-19 vaccinations are offered to different groups in the following order:    1.  Health care personnel caring for coronavirus patients as well as personnel and residents in round-the-clock care facilities    1.1 Personnel in intensive care units    1.2  Personnel in inpatient wards and emergency wards treating diagnosed or suspected COVID-19 patients and emergency care personnel    1.3 Personnel at infectious diseases clinics treating diagnosed or suspected COVID-19 patients, COVID-19 testing personnel, and laboratory personnel involved in COVID-19 diagnostics    1.4 Personnel and residents in social services for residential care and enhanced institutional, round-the-clock care units (groups 3 and 4 may be vaccinated simultaneously)    1.5 A limited number of critical personnel in social welfare and health care, for example, personnel in organ transplant units    2.1 The elderly, and persons with underlying conditions that predispose to severe COVID-19    2.1.1. 80-year-olds and older, including carers and elderly living in the same household    2.1.2. 7579-year-olds, including carers and elderly living in the same household    2.1.3. 7074-year-olds, including carers and elderly living in the same household    2.1.4. 16-69-year-olds with a highly predisposing condition for severe COVID-19. Highly predisposing conditions for severe COVID-19 disease include, for example, severe chronic kidney disease, severe immunosuppressive condition (organ transplant, acute cancer treatment) and severe chronic pulmonary disease.    2.1.5. 18-69-year-olds with a predisposing condition for severe COVID-19. Predisposing conditions for severe COVID-19 include, for example, coronary artery disease and cirrhosis of the liver.    2.2  Social welfare and health care personnel    3. column55: 23 December- Vaccine Strategy Published and Approved by Haute Autorit de Sant     5 phases outlined in the document below (p79), which was translated using Google Translate:      Phase 1 (upon delivery of the first available doses)  Elderly people at high risk of death due to their advanced age and their type of community residence: residents of establishments welcoming the elderly and residents in long-stay services (USLD )  In a probable context of limitation of the doses initially available: professionals working in establishments receiving elderly people (primarily in EHPAD, USLD) who themselves have an increased risk of severe form / death (over 65 years of age and / or presence of comorbidity (ies) 14)    Phase 2:   People over 75 years old, starting with the most elderly / with one or more comorbidities  Then people aged 65-74, prioritizing those with or several comorbidities (identified as a confirmed risk of form severe or death) in the event of insufficient doses  Professionals in the health and medico-social sectors aged 50 years and over and / or presenting one or more comorbidity (s) whatever the mode of exercise    Phase 3   People at risk because of their age (50 years-65 years) or comorbidity (s) and not previously vaccinated.   Health professionals and the medico-social sector, mentioned in the previous phases not previously vaccinated  Essential operators and professionals in essential sectors in charge education in close contact with the public or operators essential essential for the country's economic activities    Phase 4   Vulnerable and precarious people (homeless), living in communities (prisons, psychiatric establishments, homes) not previously vaccinated because of their age or co-morbidity.  Professionals taking care of vulnerable people including social workers not previously vaccinated because of their age or comorbidity.  People living in confined accommodation or working in enclosed places favoring the acquisition of infection (building workers, slaughterhouses, etc.) not previously vaccinated because of their age or comorbidity.    Phase 5   Other sections of the population likely to be infected (18-50 years old) and not previously targeted      https://web.archive.org/web/20210517112813/https://www.has-sante.fr/upload/docs/application/pdf/2020-12/strategie_vaccination_covid_19_place_vaccin_a_arnm_comirnaty_bnt162b2.pdf

column107: 30 April    Around 400,000 workers over the age of 55, in about twenty trades, will be able to be vaccinated against Covid-19 as a priority from April 24, franceinfo learned from the Ministry of Labor on Tuesday April 20.    The selection criteria chosen by the government are the fact of working in a closed environment, of being in the impossibility by virtue of his activity to respect barrier gestures, of not being able to telework and to be, according to a study by the Institut Pasteur , particularly at risk.    About twenty trades have been defined using this methodology, according to the list published by the Ministry of Labor:     Bus, ferry and river shuttle drivers, delivery men, truck drivers.   Taxi and VTC drivers.   Public transport controllers.    Maintenance workers: cleaning, waste collection and waste sorting centers.   Guard and security officers.   Employees of food stores: cashiers, self-service employees, food vendors including butchers, pork butchers, caterers, bakers, pastry chefs (business manager included).   Professional funeral directors.   Unskilled workers in the agrifood industry: employees of slaughterhouses and employees of meat processing companies.      https://web.archive.org/web/20210430151158/https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/vaccin/covid-19-chauffeurs-routiers-caissiers-eboueurs-le-gouvernement-dresse-une-liste-d-une-vingtaine-de-metiers-prioritaires-pour-se-faire-vacciner_4379421.html

column55: This prioritised list was published on 2 December 2020, as 'Priority groups for coronavirus (COVID-19) vaccination: advice from the JCVI, 2 December 2020' on this government site:  https://web.archive.org/web/20201202231629/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/priority-groups-for-coronavirus-covid-19-vaccination-advice-from-the-jcvi-2-december-2020/priority-groups-for-coronavirus-covid-19-vaccination-advice-from-the-jcvi-2-december-2020     This priority list is as follows:     1.residents in a care home for older adults and their carers  2.all those 80 years of age and over and frontline health and social care workers  3.all those 75 years of age and over  4.all those 70 years of age and over and clinically extremely vulnerable individuals[footnote 1]  5.all those 65 years of age and over  6.all individuals aged 16 years to 64 years with underlying health conditions which put them at higher risk of serious disease and mortality  7.all those 60 years of age and over  8.all those 55 years of age and over  9.all those 50 years of age and over     It is estimated that taken together, these groups represent around 99% of preventable mortality from COVID-19.

column55: 8 Dec 2020      Priority list published by Irish government on 8 December 2020. Where the categories on this list don't fit the V1 categories perfectly, I have coded a 'best fit' if possible, or excluded category. Excluded '4.Other healthcare workers not in direct patient contact' and 'residents of long term care aged 18-64', and 'other workers in occupations important to the functioning of society' because this was not specified. Coded 'key workers' as 'frontline workers', and 'people aged 18-54' including the 16+ category.    1. Your quick guide to the provisional vaccine allocation groups  2. Provisional vaccine allocation groups  3. Download this information  The COVID-19 Vaccine Allocation Strategy sets out a provisional priority list of groups for vaccination once a safe and effective vaccine(s) has received authorisation from the European Medicines Agency (EMA).    The Strategy was developed by the National Immunisation Advisory Committee (NIAC) and Department of Health, endorsed by the National Public Health Emergency Team (NPHET), and approved by Government on 8 December 2020.    The Strategy is a further component to the States response to the COVID-19 pandemic, and will evolve and adapt with more detailed information on the vaccines and their effectiveness.    Your quick guide to the provisional vaccine allocation groups  This is the provisional order in which people in Ireland will be vaccinated against COVID-19.    1	People aged 65 years and older who are residents of long-term care facilities (likely to include all staff and residents on site)  2	Frontline healthcare workers  3	People aged 70 and older  4	Other healthcare workers not in direct patient contact  5	People aged 65-69  6	Key workers  7	People aged 18-64 with certain medical conditions  8	Residents of long-term care facilities aged 18-64  9	People aged 18-64 living or working in crowded settings  10	Key workers in essential jobs who cannot avoid a high risk of exposure  11	People working in education sector  12	People aged 55-64  13	Other workers in occupations important to the functioning of society  14	Other people aged 18-54  15	People aged under 18 and pregnant women      https://web.archive.org/web/20201208122426/https://www.gov.ie/en/publication/39038-provisional-vaccine-allocation-groups/

16 December 2020    Israel publishes its priority list on 16 December 2021. On Sunday, December 20th, 2020, the first phase of the vaccination campaign begins.    In Phase A, healthcare personnel will be vaccinated    - Expandion [sic] of Stage A Age 60 or older. Vaccination of adults aged 60 and over and at-risk populations is expected to begin next week. As part of the vaccination at Kupoth Holim clinics, flexibility must be exercised while vaccinating. For example, an elderly person in the community and the accompanier or caregiver. Another example of flexibility is for caregivers of special-risk populations such as lung transplant recipients.    Phase B - Expanding the circle of vaccines for the entire population in the following order:    - Continued vaccination of risk groups: Diabetes, morbid obesity, COPD, hypertension, patients with immunosuppression, organ transplant recipients, hematologic patients and the like. It should be noted that the group of patients with immunosuppression should include family and family members with precedence.  - High-exposure groups such as teachers, kindergarten teachers, social workers, prisons, prisoners and prison guards  - The IDF and security bodies will receive an allocation in accordance with a vaccination plan that will be presented to the Ministry  Next - opening the vaccination to the entire population as scheduled by the Kupoth Holim    The following populations will not be vaccinated at this time:    Children and youth up to the age of 16  Recovering individuals  Pregnant Women  Breastfeeding women  People with a history of severe hypersensitivity reactions - anaphylaxis  Women planning to become pregnant - up to a month after receiving a second vaccine    https://web.archive.org/web/20210423144051/https://www.gov.il/en/departments/news/16122020-01

column55: The Japanese government's coronavirus countermeasures subcommittee presented a plan on Dec. 23 regarding priority groups for COVID-19 vaccines, and how they will be carried out.    The subcommittee, headed by chairman Shigeru Omi, proposed that health care workers and others who frequently come into contact with infected individuals be vaccinated first. The plan outlined that the elderly should be the next group to be administered vaccinations, followed by patients with underlying conditions, as well as staff at care facilities for the elderly.    Under the proposed framework, people aged 65 years or older are considered elderly, and those with underlying conditions include chronic respiratory illness, cardiac disease, kidney disease, cancer, as well as people with a body mass index level of at least 30 who receive regular treatment at or are admitted to hospitals. The framework will be finalized by the end of January next year.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210506145146/https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20201224/p2a/00m/0na/007000c

Cannot find specific date which vaccine priority groups were officially announced but media sources from 20 January detail them. Official source from February details the specifics of the eligible groups so this source is also included below. The government has said it would prioritise medical workers, the elderly, and those with pre-existing conditions in its vaccine programme expected to start by the end of February but has not provided a timeline beyond that. GROUPS: Therefore, the Government intends to administer vaccines in the following order: 1) health care professionals and others who provide medical treatment for COVID-19 patients and others directly, 2) persons aged 65 or higher (While vaccinations are scheduled to begin for those who will reach 65 years of age during FY 2021 (people born on or before April 1, 1957), the time period may be further divided) 3) staff who interact directly with people having underlying conditions or users of elderly care facilities. Media source: https://web.archive.org/web/20210506150825/https://www.reuters.com/business/healthcare-pharmaceuticals/japans-vaccine-programme-chief-denies-reports-may-roll-out-2021-01-20/ Official information (in English) about eligible groups https://web.archive.org/web/20210225090739/https://japan.kantei.go.jp/ongoingtopics/vaccine.html https://web.archive.org/web/20210506145049/https://www.mhlw.go.jp/content/000759274.pdf

column55: Source 1 contains a helpful table with the Q1, Q2, Q3, and Q4 vaccination groups to be vaccinated in order in South Korea.    Q1  1- Workers and patients at nursing homes aged under 65  1- Medical workers at COVID-19 treatment centers  2- Medical workers at 'high risk' from medical institutions  2- COVID-19 Frontline responders (epidemiological investigators, 119 emergency workers, etc)    Q2  3- Citizens aged over 65  3- Workers at medical institutions and pharmacies who have not been vaccinated in Q1  3- Workers and patients at facilities for the disabled, homeless shelters    Q3  4- Citizens aged from 18-65  4- Adults with chronic illnesses  4- Social service workers such as military service members, police, firefighters  4- Workers in education facilities for children    Q4  5- Unvaccinated people        Source 2: 'The Korea Disease Control and Prevention Agency announced on Monday [15 February 2021] that 272,000 people and patients at nursing homes and other high-risk facilities will be the first to receive the vaccine starting February 26. But shots for seniors 65 and older will be put on hold until further information on efficacy for the age group is obtained. KDCA Director Jeong Eun-kyeong explained during a press briefing that elderly people will likely get their shots in the second quarter, possibly with AstraZeneca's two-dose regimen or another vaccine made by Novavax. From March 8, vaccinations for will begin for 354,000 medical workers at general hospitals with a high number of COVID-19 patients with severe symptoms. Around 78,000 others on the coronavirus frontlines, including paramedics, quarantine officers and epidemiological investigators, will get vaccines starting March 22, the KDCA said.Initially, the agency said 760,000 health care workers and the elderly would be among the first to get vaccinated between February and March as part of a greater goal to get 70 percent of South Korea's population of 52 million inoculated by September.The government aims to achieve herd immunity by November, and earlier confirmed that it has secured enough vaccines through the WHO-backed COVID-19 Vaccine Global Access (COVAX) Facility and separate contracts with four foreign drug firms to inoculate 56 million people.The first shipment of the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine is expected to arrive in the country by early March.'        Source 1: https://archive.vn/2ib6q    Source 2: https://archive.vn/PaNPo

column55: There is an ongoing process of defining which groups to recommend vaccine.    Risk groups include:    - residents in nursing homes  - people over 65 years  - people aged 1864 who have one or more of the diseases that are known to give an increased risk of severe disease course or death if they develop coronavirus.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201208084304/https://www.fhi.no/en/id/vaccines/coronavirus-immunisation-programme/coronavirus-vaccine/

Priority list is published 21 December 2020 Order of priority: 1. Residents in nursing homes 2. Age 85 years and above 3. Age 75-84 years 4. Age 65-74 years AND people between 18 and 64 years with these diseases/conditions: organ transplant immunodeficiency hematologic (blood) cancer in the last 5 years other active cancer, ongoing or recently finished treatment for cancer (especially immunosuppressive therapy, radiation therapy to the lungs or chemotherapy). neurological or muscular disease with impaired coughing strength or lung function chronic kidney disease and kidney failure 5. Age 55-64 years with these diseases/conditions: Chronic liver disease or significantly impaired liver function Immunosuppressive therapy, e.g. with autoimmune diseases Diabetes Chronic lung disease* Obesity with body mass index (BMI of = 35 kg/m2 or higher) Dementia Chronic cardiovascular disease (except high blood pressure) Stroke Other serious and / or chronic diseases not mentioned in the list above may also increase the risk of serious illness and death from COVID-19. This should be assessed individually by a doctor. 6. Age 45-54 years with the same diseases/ conditions listed in point 5 7. Age 18-44 years with the same diseases/ conditions listed in point 5 8. Age 55-64 years 9. Age 45-54 years * Asthma is considered to be a chronic lung disease among people who regularly use inhaled steroids or cortisone tablets. People who occasionally use fast-acting reliever inhalers are not considered to have a chronic lung disease. It may be appropriate to recommend the vaccine to a larger part of the population when we know more about the vaccines that are approved and how the pandemic develops. Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201224192753/https://www.fhi.no/en/id/vaccines/coronavirus-immunisation-programme/who-will-get-coronavirus-vaccine-first/

column55: The Swedish Public Health Agency will produce recommendations for which persons should be offered vaccination against covid-19. A basic principle is that the people who have the greatest need for protection against serious illness should be offered vaccination first.    Based on the current state of knowledge and experience, the order of priority would look like this:    People who are 70 years and older, as well as people with underlying conditions that often occur in severe covid-19 disease, should be given priority to be offered vaccination against covid-19. Here you can read more about the risk groups .  In addition, staff in elderly care, health care and other care staff who work closely with people at risk of severe covid-19 should be given priority in order to be offered vaccination against covid-19, in order to prevent the spread of infection and disease.  Thereafter, other parts of the population from the age of 18 and up may be offered vaccination.  These priorities can also be affected by which vaccines become available and how the vaccines work.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201109174717/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/vaccination-mot-covid-19/

The chairman of the task force created by the Portuguese government to define the covid-19 vaccination plan Francisco Ramos presented this Thursday, December 3, the first details of the vaccination process which will begin in January 2021. The vaccine will not be mandatory. First phase of vaccination (January-March / April): - People aged 50 or over, with at least one of the following pathologies: heart failure, coronary artery disease, renal failure and chronic respiratory disease with ventilatory assistance (400,000 people) - Residents at home and hospitalized in continuing care units, and their professionals (250,000 people) - Health professionals directly involved in the provision of care and the staff of the armed forces and security forces - considered essential and critical services, the list of which remains to be refined (300,000 people) Second phase of vaccination (from the second trimester): - 65 years and over, with or without pathologies (1.8 million people) - Group between 50 and 74 years old, with extension of pre-existing pathologies, such as diabetes, active malignancy, chronic renal failure, hepatic failure, obesity and arterial hypertension. (900,000 people) Third phase of vaccination (to be confirmed): - Rest of the population, if the expected rate of vaccine supply is confirmed. If for some reason this pace is much slower than the current baseline scenario, authorities will need to create a third priority group. https://web.archive.org/web/20210511083607/https://www.lisbob.net/en/blog/all-measures-in-place-for-christmas-and-new-year-in-portugal-ny9gn

27 December Ministry of Health publishes the priority population subgroups for vaccination. I have adjusted the priority rankings to reflect this    1. Persons at high risk of being infected by COVID-19, including healthcare workers and workers at the frontline of our national COVID-19 response.  2. Persons who are most vulnerable to severe disease and complications if they fall ill with COVID-19, including the elderly and persons with vascular medical comorbidities. column55: The Swedish Public Health Agency has been commissioned by the government to develop a national plan for vaccination against covid-19. The Swedish Public Health Agency recommends that the following groups be vaccinated first: 1- People who live in special housing for the elderly or have home care (mainly persons who are 70 years and older) 2- Personnel in elderly care, health and medical care and other care personnel who work close to people as above. 3- Close household contacts to people who have home care/Adults who live with people who have home care. https://web.archive.org/web/20201204221611/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/publicerat-material/publikationsarkiv/n/nationell-plan-for-vaccination-mot-covid-19/ https://web.archive.org/web/20201212235330/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/vaccination-mot-covid-19/ https://web.archive.org/web/20201205084706/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/contentassets/f8703f0a29cc408fb788b60f87289e5b/nationell-plan-vaccination-covid-19.pdf

18 December priority list updated: Phase 1 -Persons who live in special housing for the elderly or have home care in ordinary housing. This mainly applies to people who are 70 years and older. -Personnel in elderly care who work close to residents and care recipients -Household contacts, ie. adults living with someone who belongs to the risk group Phase 2 and 3 Other people who are 70 years and older. Other care and nursing staff who work closely with patients and care recipients with an increased risk of becoming seriously ill with covid-19. Other people who are 1869 years old and belong to a risk group. The work of specifying priorities and risk groups is ongoing. Phase 4 The last group to be offered vaccination are other adults: 18 years and older who do not belong to any risk group. https://web.archive.org/web/20201218214314/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/vaccination-mot-covid-19/rekommendationer-for-vaccination-mot-covid-19/

column55: 04 February 2021- Priority list is updated and expanded: Phase 1 - In a first phase, which began at the end of December 2020, those living in special housing for the elderly or having home care under the Social Services Act, staff working close to these people, and adults living with someone belonging to this risk group are vaccinated. Phase 2 - The second phase includes the following risk groups: people aged 65 and over, of which the oldest are vaccinated first people who have undergone bone marrow or other organ transplants in the last 12 months and their household contacts people with dialysis treatment and their household contacts persons who are 18 years or older who receive contributions in accordance with the Act (1993: 387) on support and services for certain disabled people (LSS) persons who are 18 years or older who have a decision on assistance compensation according to the Social Insurance Code. The oldest are offered vaccination first health and care staff (including LSS), who work closely with patients and care recipients. Phase 3 The third phase includes the following risk groups: - Persons aged 60-64 years with a disease or condition that involves an increase in risk (according to the list below) - persons aged 6064 years - persons aged 18-59 years with a disease or condition that involves an increase in risk (according to the list below) - persons with conditions that make it difficult to follow advice on infection control measures. This applies to people aged 18-59 with dementia and cognitive or mental disabilities. This also applies to people who live in socially vulnerable situations, such as the homeless or the undocumented. - Diseases or conditions that carry an increased risk of severe covid-19: Chronic cardiovascular disease, including stroke and hypertension chronic lung disease such as COPD and severe and unstable asthma Other conditions leading to impaired lung function or impaired coughing and secretion stagnation (eg extreme obesity, neuromuscular diseases or multiple disabilities) chronic liver or kidney failure type 1 and type 2 diabetes conditions that involve severely weakened immune systems due to illness or treatment Down syndrome. Phase 4 The fourth and final phase includes people 18 years and older who have not been prioritized in previous phases. The groups that are to be prioritized first are support for the regions 'work with vaccinations and a basis for decisions based on the regions' different conditions. The Swedish Public Health Agency and the regions work together to implement these vaccination initiatives. https://web.archive.org/web/20210205000954/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/vaccination-mot-covid-19/rekommendationer-for-vaccination-mot-covid-19/

column107: In Srmland, phase 3 opens for vaccination on 29 April. If you have a disease or condition that involves an increased risk of becoming seriously ill with covid-19, you are given priority for vaccination in phase 3. Which ones apply? You who have a chronic cardiovascular disease. You who have a chronic lung disease, such as COPD or severe asthma. You who have a very strong overweight. You who have a neuromuscular disease that affects breathing. You who have several disabilities. You who have chronic liver failure or kidney failure. You who have type 1 diabetes or type 2 diabetes. You who have a severely weakened immune system due to an illness or a treatment. You who have Down syndrome. You who are pregnant and have one or more risk factors, for example are over 35 years old, have a BMI over 30 or other conditions or diseases that increase the risk of becoming seriously ill with covid-19.

All regions now appear to be in Phase 4 (all adults, offered in a staggered way, opening up to five-year age groups at a time): everyone over 50 (and in many regions younger than that, too) is now eligible to get vaccinated.     Details per region:   http://web.archive.org/web/20210604185515/https://www.thelocal.se/20210414/where-is-the-vaccination-programme-up-to-in-swedens-21-regions/  http://web.archive.org/web/20210604185525/https://www.krisinformation.se/detta-kan-handa/handelser-och-storningar/20192/myndigheterna-om-det-nya-coronaviruset/regional-information-om-coronaviruset    Type of vaccine: Pfizer, Moderna, AstraZeneca    - Details on delivery of the 3 vaccines in use: http://web.archive.org/web/20210604185803/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/covid-19/statistik-och-analyser/leveranser-av-vaccin/  - The use of the Janssen vaccin is suspended for all age groups. "The vaccine is not recommended for people under 65, and those over 65 will have received other vaccines before Janssen's vaccine can be delivered." http://web.archive.org/web/20210507150759/https://www.krisinformation.se/nyheter/20212/april2/fortsatt-paus-for-janssens-vaccin   - The recommendation to only use AstraZeneca for people over 65 remains: http://web.archive.org/web/20210507150801/https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/nyheter-och-press/nyhetsarkiv/2021/april/rekommendation-om-aldersgrans-pa-65-ar-for-astrazenecas-vaccin-kvarstar/   But anyone under the age of 65 who has already received a first dose of Astra Zeneca's vaccine can also receive their second dose of the same vaccine if they specifically request it. On March 9, 2021, Alaska becomes the first state to move to opening vaccines for all residents over the age of 16yrs+ (the lowest age currently approved for COVID vaccine use in the US at the time).     The CDC recommended priorities still remain, but as universal de jury policy is beginning to move in, have update V1 prioritisation to account for this:     On December 1, 2020, the CDC and the ACIP RECOMMENDED that two groups be prioritised for COVID-19 vaccine distribution: healthcare personnel and residents of long-term care facilities.     As each state has the ability to make it's own decision on which groups of people will be prioritised, and when, these are the only national level recommendations/guidelines.     http://web.archive.org/web/20201222024926/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/recommendations-process.html

column55: On March 9, 2021, Alaska becomes the first state to move to opening vaccines for all residents over the age of 16yrs+ (the lowest age currently approved for COVID vaccine use in the US at the time).     The CDC recommended priorities still remain, but as universal de jury policy is beginning to move in, have update V1 prioritisation to account for this:     On December 1, 2020, the CDC and the ACIP RECOMMENDED that two groups be prioritised for COVID-19 vaccine distribution: healthcare personnel and residents of long-term care facilities.     As each state has the ability to make it's own decision on which groups of people will be prioritised, and when, these are the only national level recommendations/guidelines.     http://web.archive.org/web/20201222024926/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/recommendations-process.html
